<REASONING>
In this public goods game, contributing to the public fund benefits everyone due to the multiplier effect, but free-riding (contributing nothing) might appear to offer a higher immediate individual benefit if others contribute. However, contributing nothing risks longer-term penalties through deductions if others see me as not cooperating and decide to punish me. 

The optimal strategy considers both maximizing the payoff and minimizing the risk of deductions. If I contribute nothing, there's a significant risk that others will punish me, outweighing any potential gain from trying to free-ride on the contributions of others. 

Given the group dynamics and the one-off nature of the game, contributing all coins can help encourage cooperation and guard against deductions, which would reduce my final payoff. This strategy aims to maximize potential group earnings, which, due to the multiplier, ultimately increases individual returns if at least some others also contribute.

Thus, I choose to contribute everything in hopes of other rational players understanding the collective benefit and also contributing, leading to a higher payoff for everyone.
